[Today's global update from WHO (see [1] above) mentions an additional 72
cases and 4 deaths since the last global update issued on 29 Mar 2003. The
update from the Hong Kong Department of Health mentions an additional 80
cases reported since 30 Mar 2003. The data for case reports from Hong Kong
contained in the WHO update are for cases reported as of 30 Mar 2003 and do
not reflect the additional 80 cases reported in Hong Kong as of 31 Mar 2003.
The report out of Hong Kong re: the association of cases with a vertical
block of apartments in Kowloon is noteworthy, though it is still very early
in the investigation to draw conclusions re: transmission. We will be
following this closely and will report information as it becomes
available. The decision to implement a quarantine of the residents of this
building may seem severe, but given the many unknowns about SARS, and the
observation that there may be a different form of transmission other than
"close contact" here as seen elsewhere, it is hard to be critical of the
Hong Kong Department of Health at this juncture. Elsewhere transmission
still seems to be following a pattern consistent with a need for close
contact with SARS cases.
Roger Feldman MD <Feldmanmail@aol.com> has raised excellent questions about
more detailed epidemiologic information on this outbreak, such as
age-specific case fatality rates, secondary attack rates, more details on
the clinical course, etc. We have tried to present a synopsis of data
available to us at ProMED-mail, and we too look forward to reports
containing more detailed epidemiologic data on this outbreak that we could
share with our readers. It needs to be highlighted that current
investigations use case definitions that are based on clinical and
epidemiological criteria. Clinical criteria include a disease spectrum
that is shared by many other etiologies, especially at this time of year in
the northern hemisphere, and the current epidemiologic criteria include
contact with previously identified cases or presence in geographic areas
with identified local transmission. More definitive details will be
available once an etiologic agent is definitively identified and laboratory
testing becomes available to permit confirmation of true cases of what is
now being referred to as SARS. We've learned a lot about this new emerging
infectious disease in a very short amount of time, but much more will be
learned as more data become available. - Mod.MPP]
